    <div class="related-tools">
      <h3>Related Tools</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/grading-calculator">Grading Calculator</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding Tire Sizes and the Mathematics of Plus-Sizing</h2>
      <p>Whether you are upgrading to a larger set of off-road tires, lowering your sports car on low-profile rubber, or simply shopping for winter replacements, understanding tire dimensions is crucial. Modifying your vehicle's tire size is not just an aesthetic choice; it is a mechanical alteration that impacts handling, gearing, fuel economy, and crucially, the accuracy of your vehicle's instruments. Our tire calculator bridges the gap between the cryptic numbers stamped on your sidewall and real-world physical dimensions.</p>

      <h3>Decoding the Tire Sidewall</h3>
      <p>Most modern passenger vehicles use the P-Metric or Euro-Metric tire sizing systems. A typical tire size looks like this: <strong>225/45R17</strong>. While it looks like a continuous serial number, it is actually a highly specific formula containing mixed units of metric and imperial measurements.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Width (225):</strong> The first number represents the section width of the tire in millimeters. This is the measurement of the tire from sidewall to sidewall at its widest point when mounted on the correct rim.</li>
        <li><strong>Aspect Ratio (45):</strong> The second number is a percentage, not a direct measurement. It tells you the height of the tire's sidewall relative to its width. In this example, the sidewall height is 45% of the 225mm width.</li>
        <li><strong>Construction (R):</strong> The "R" stands for Radial construction, which is the industry standard for almost all modern road tires.</li>
        <li><strong>Wheel Diameter (17):</strong> The final number represents the diameter of the wheel (rim) that the tire is designed to fit, measured in inches.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Mathematics of Tire Geometry</h3>
      <p>Because tire sizes mix millimeters, percentages, and inches, calculating the physical dimensions requires converting all values into a single unit—typically inches, as it is the standard for wheel diameters.</p>

      <h4>Calculating Sidewall Height</h4>
      <p>To find the height of the rubber sidewall, you must multiply the tire width by the aspect ratio percentage, and then convert that metric result into inches by dividing by 25.4 (since there are 25.4 millimeters in exactly one inch).</p>
      <p class="formula-box"><strong>Sidewall (in) = (Width × (Aspect Ratio ÷ 100)) ÷ 25.4</strong></p>

      <h4>Calculating Overall Diameter</h4>
      <p>The overall diameter of the mounted tire is the combination of the metal wheel diameter plus the rubber sidewall on the top and the rubber sidewall on the bottom. Therefore, you must multiply the sidewall height by two before adding the wheel diameter.</p>
      <p class="formula-box"><strong>Overall Diameter = (Sidewall × 2) + Wheel Diameter</strong></p>

      <h4>Calculating Circumference and Revolutions Per Mile</h4>
      <p>Once the overall diameter is established, calculating the circumference (the distance the tire travels in one complete rotation) is a simple application of pi (π).</p>
      <p class="formula-box"><strong>Circumference = Diameter × π</strong></p>
      <p>To find out how many times the tire rotates in exactly one mile (5,280 feet or 63,360 inches), you divide the total inches in a mile by the tire's circumference in inches.</p>
      <p class="formula-box"><strong>Revolutions Per Mile = 63,360 ÷ Circumference</strong></p>

      <h3>The Hidden Impact on Your Speedometer</h3>
      <p>Your vehicle's speedometer does not actually measure your speed over the ground via GPS. Instead, the vehicle's computer relies on a speed sensor located in the transmission or wheel hub that counts the rotational speed of the drivetrain. The computer is programmed at the factory with the exact circumference of the stock tires, assuming that every single revolution equals a specific distance traveled.</p>

      <p>When you change the overall diameter of your tires, you alter that foundational math. If you install a tire with a larger diameter (and therefore a larger circumference), your vehicle will travel further down the road for every single revolution of the axle than it did before. Because the computer does not know you changed the tires, it still calculates speed based on the smaller factory circumference.</p>

      <p>The result? <strong>With larger tires, your actual road speed will be faster than what your speedometer displays.</strong> This is a common trap that leads to speeding tickets for drivers who install aggressive off-road tires or larger aftermarket wheels. Conversely, if you install smaller tires, they have to spin faster to cover the same distance, meaning your speedometer will read artificially high, tricking you into driving slower than the flow of traffic.</p>

      <h3>The 3% Golden Rule of Tire Sizing</h3>
      <p>While upgrading your wheels can drastically improve the look and performance of a vehicle, automotive engineers and tire professionals adhere strictly to the "3% Rule." This industry standard dictates that the overall diameter of any replacement tire should remain within 3% (plus or minus) of the original factory tire diameter.</p>

      <p>Why is this limitation so strict? Modern vehicles are highly complex networks of interlinked computers. Systems like Anti-lock Braking Systems (ABS), Electronic Stability Control (ESC), and Traction Control constantly monitor the rotational speed of all four wheels. If the tire diameter is altered drastically, the rotational data falls out of the expected parameters. This can cause these critical safety systems to trigger prematurely or fail to activate entirely during an emergency.</p>

      <p>Furthermore, significant changes in tire diameter alter the vehicle's final drive ratio. A dramatically larger tire acts like a taller gear in the transmission, reducing low-end acceleration, straining the transmission, increasing braking distance, and often ruining fuel economy. The 3% rule ensures that the mechanical and electronic systems continue to function as safely and efficiently as the manufacturer intended.</p>

      <h3>Using the Calculator to Plan Plus-Sizing</h3>
      <p>A common modification technique is "Plus-Sizing" (Plus-1, Plus-2, etc.), which involves installing a larger diameter wheel while simultaneously reducing the tire's aspect ratio (sidewall height) to maintain the identical overall factory diameter.</p>

      <p>For example, if you want to upgrade from a 17-inch wheel to an 18-inch wheel, you cannot simply use the same tire specifications on the new rim. Using our calculator, you can experiment with inputting a wider tire width and a lower aspect ratio on the new 18-inch rim until the overall diameter matches your stock baseline. This allows you to achieve the sportier look and stiffer handling of a larger wheel and lower profile tire without breaking the 3% rule, throwing off your speedometer, or compromising vehicle safety systems.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What do the numbers on my tire mean?</summary>
        <p>The numbers on a tire (like 225/45R17) represent three key dimensions. The first number (225) is the tire width in millimeters. The second number (45) is the aspect ratio, meaning the sidewall height is 45% of the width. The final number (17) is the wheel/rim diameter in inches.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does tire size affect my speedometer?</summary>
        <p>Your car's computer measures speed based on wheel rotations. If you install larger diameter tires, they cover more ground per rotation than the stock tires. As a result, your speedometer will read slower than your actual speed. Conversely, smaller tires make the speedometer read faster than your actual speed.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I calculate overall tire diameter?</summary>
        <p>To calculate overall tire diameter in inches: first, find the sidewall height in millimeters by multiplying the width by the aspect ratio percentage. Convert that height to inches by dividing by 25.4. Finally, multiply the sidewall height in inches by 2 (for top and bottom) and add the wheel diameter.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the maximum tire size change recommended?</summary>
        <p>Automotive experts generally recommend keeping your new tire diameter within 3% of the original factory tire diameter. Exceeding this 3% rule can severely impact your vehicle's anti-lock braking system (ABS), traction control, speedometer accuracy, and transmission shifting points.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Will wider tires fit on my current rims?</summary>
        <p>Wider tires can sometimes fit on stock rims, but every rim width has an approved range of tire widths. If you mount a tire that is too wide for the rim, the sidewalls will bulge excessively, leading to poor handling and dangerous bead seat failures. Always consult the tire manufacturer's rim width specifications.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      // Inputs
      const w1 = document.getElementById('width1');
      const a1 = document.getElementById('aspect1');
      const r1 = document.getElementById('rim1');

      const w2 = document.getElementById('width2');
      const a2 = document.getElementById('aspect2');
      const r2 = document.getElementById('rim2');

      const err1 = document.getElementById('error1');
      const err2 = document.getElementById('error2');

      // Stock outputs
      const outDia1 = document.getElementById('dia1');
      const outWid1 = document.getElementById('wid1');
      const outSw1 = document.getElementById('sw1');
      const outCirc1 = document.getElementById('circ1');
      const outRevs1 = document.getElementById('revs1');

      // New outputs
      const outDia2 = document.getElementById('dia2');
      const outWid2 = document.getElementById('wid2');
      const outSw2 = document.getElementById('sw2');
      const outCirc2 = document.getElementById('circ2');
      const outRevs2 = document.getElementById('revs2');

      // Diffs
      const diffDia = document.getElementById('diaDiff');
      const diffWid = document.getElementById('widDiff');
      const diffSw = document.getElementById('swDiff');
      const diffCirc = document.getElementById('circDiff');
      const diffRevs = document.getElementById('revsDiff');

      const actualSpeed = document.getElementById('actualSpeed');
      const warningMsg = document.getElementById('warningMsg');

      function calculateTire(w, a, r) {
        // Validation
        if (!w || !a || !r || w < 100 || w > 400 || a < 20 || a > 90 || r < 10 || r > 30) {
            return null;
        }

        const widthIn = w / 25.4;
        const sidewallIn = widthIn * (a / 100);
        const diameter = (sidewallIn * 2) + r;
        const circumference = diameter * Math.PI;
        const revsPerMile = 63360 / circumference;

        return {
          diameter: diameter,
          width: widthIn,
          sidewall: sidewallIn,
          circumference: circumference,
          revs: revsPerMile
        };
      }

      function formatDiff(val, unit, isPercentage = false) {
        const sign = val >= 0 ? '+' : '';
        const num = isPercentage ? val.toFixed(1) : val.toFixed(1);
        return sign + num + unit;
      }

      function updateDiffStyle(el, val) {
        el.className = 'diff';
        if (val > 0) el.classList.add('positive');
        if (val < 0) el.classList.add('negative');
      }

      function update() {
        err1.style.display = 'none';
        err2.style.display = 'none';

        const t1 = calculateTire(parseFloat(w1.value), parseFloat(a1.value), parseFloat(r1.value));
        const t2 = calculateTire(parseFloat(w2.value), parseFloat(a2.value), parseFloat(r2.value));

        if (!t1) {
            err1.textContent = 'Invalid stock tire dimensions.';
            err1.style.display = 'block';
            return;
        }
        if (!t2) {
            err2.textContent = 'Invalid new tire dimensions.';
            err2.style.display = 'block';
            return;
        }

        // Output T1
        outDia1.textContent = t1.diameter.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outWid1.textContent = t1.width.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outSw1.textContent = t1.sidewall.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outCirc1.textContent = t1.circumference.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outRevs1.textContent = Math.round(t1.revs);

        // Output T2
        outDia2.textContent = t2.diameter.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outWid2.textContent = t2.width.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outSw2.textContent = t2.sidewall.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outCirc2.textContent = t2.circumference.toFixed(1) + '"';
        outRevs2.textContent = Math.round(t2.revs);

        // Diffs
        const diaPcnt = ((t2.diameter - t1.diameter) / t1.diameter) * 100;
        diffDia.textContent = formatDiff(diaPcnt, '%', true);
        updateDiffStyle(diffDia, diaPcnt);

        const widDiffVal = t2.width - t1.width;
        diffWid.textContent = formatDiff(widDiffVal, '"');
        updateDiffStyle(diffWid, widDiffVal);

        const swDiffVal = t2.sidewall - t1.sidewall;
        diffSw.textContent = formatDiff(swDiffVal, '"');
        updateDiffStyle(diffSw, swDiffVal);

        const circDiffVal = t2.circumference - t1.circumference;
        diffCirc.textContent = formatDiff(circDiffVal, '"');
        updateDiffStyle(diffCirc, circDiffVal);

        const revsDiffVal = t2.revs - t1.revs;
        diffRevs.textContent = formatDiff(revsDiffVal, '');
        updateDiffStyle(diffRevs, revsDiffVal);

        // Speedometer
        const testSpeed = 60;
        // If new tire is bigger, you travel farther per rev, meaning actual speed is higher than speedo.
        // Ratio is new_circumference / old_circumference
        const speedRatio = t2.circumference / t1.circumference;
        const realSpeed = testSpeed * speedRatio;

        actualSpeed.textContent = realSpeed.toFixed(1) + ' mph';

        if (Math.abs(diaPcnt) > 3) {
            warningMsg.style.display = 'flex';
        } else {
            warningMsg.style.display = 'none';
        }
      }

      const inputs = document.querySelectorAll('input');
      inputs.forEach(input => {
        input.addEventListener('input', update);
      });

      // Initial run
      update();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
